== SPI streaming slave (raw)

A deliberately minimal SPI slave that exists for one purpose: pin
down the maximum SCLK frequency the iCE40-HX1K can sustain when
the wire protocol is stripped of every framing byte. The MP135
host drives a raw indirect read --- IMODE=0, ADMODE=0, no dummy
--- so every SCLK cycle inside CS-low carries useful payload.
The slave's job is to put the next byte of an incrementing
`A[7:0]` pattern on the bus, in lockstep with SCLK, with no
opcode latch, address capture, or dummy-cycle counter in the
critical path.

Two synthesis variants are produced from one source. `LANES=1`
drives the single-lane pattern on both `io[0]` and `io[1]` on
`negedge sclk`, MSB-first; the bench command on the host side is
`b <len> 0 1`. Driving both lanes is deliberate: the MP135
QUADSPI raw read samples IO0 in 1-line data mode even though
conventional SPI labels often call IO1/MISO the slave-output lane.
Mirroring the pattern avoids making the raw-read benchmark depend
on that naming ambiguity.
`LANES=4` drives all four lanes combinationally; the bench
command is `b <len> 1 1`. The 4-lane case follows the convention
the rest of this codebase has settled on: the STM32MP1 QUADSPI
indirect-read engine assembles each byte as
`{first_sample, second_sample}`, so the first sample of a byte
cycle carries the upper nibble and the second sample carries the
lower nibble.

=== Why explicit `SB_IO` instances

An earlier revision drove the lanes with fabric tri-state
shapes:

   wire oe = ~cs_n;
   assign io[1] = oe ? q : 1'bz;

yosys flagged this with `Warning: Yosys has only limited support
for tri-state logic` and emitted four `$_TBUF_` cells in the
generic netlist. nextpnr then placed them, but on real iCE40
silicon the lanes never drove anything --- the master read
`0xFF` for the entire megabyte transfer because the fabric
tristate path did not reach the `SB_IO` output enable, and the
master's MISO pull-up won. The simulator did not catch this
because verilator's tri-state resolution does not model a master
pull-up: an undriven net in the TB resolves to `X`, which the
existing `!==` check happens to flag in some stimulus shapes
but not in others.

The fix is to bypass tri-state inference entirely and
instantiate `SB_IO` cells directly. The 1-lane pads are configured
as `PIN_TYPE = 6'b100101` (output registered with output enable)
and `NEG_TRIGGER = 1` so the IOB's output flop captures
`D_OUT_0` on `negedge OUTPUT_CLK`. The 4-lane pads use
`PIN_TYPE = 6'b101001`, keeping the explicit output enable but
driving the nibble value unregistered. `OUTPUT_CLK = sclk`,
`OUTPUT_ENABLE = ~cs_n`. In 1-lane mode the IOB flop is the
negedge presenter: it captures the next bit half a cycle ahead of
the master's mode-0 rising-edge sample point.

=== Lane data path

The byte-pattern counter `data_byte` advances on `posedge sclk`
and is synchronously cleared whenever `cs_n` is high at the
rise. The output flop starts at the first bit/nibble of byte 0, so
the first rising edge in a frame samples valid data even before any
falling edge has occurred. The `phase` counter narrows per variant:
3 bits for 1-lane (eight rises per byte, MSB-first), 1 bit for
4-lane (two rises per byte, upper nibble first then lower).

The combinational `dout_lane[3:0]` carries the current lane value.
For 4-lane, every lane carries a real bit of the current nibble
directly to an unregistered pad. For 1-lane, `dout_lane[0]` and
`dout_lane[1]` both carry the data bit that the IOB flop will latch
at the next negedge; the other two lanes are held low when enabled.
Both variants feed a
single shared genvar loop that instantiates one `SB_IO` per pad, so
the synthesis netlist contains exactly four explicit pad drivers and
no fabric tri-state cells regardless of `LANES`.

<<spi.v>>=
module spi #(
      parameter LANES = 1
   ) (
      input        cs_n,
      input        sclk,
      inout  [3:0] io
   );
   <<SPI streaming: state>>
   <<SPI streaming: lane logic>>
   <<SPI streaming: io drivers>>
endmodule
@

`data_byte` is shared across both variants; `oe` and `dout_lane`
are the wires the IOB driver loop reads.

<<SPI streaming: state>>=
reg [7:0] data_byte;
initial data_byte = 8'd0;
wire [3:0] dout_lane;
wire oe = ~cs_n;
@

The lane logic chunk holds the per-variant `phase` register,
the edge counter, and the assignment that drives `dout_lane`
from `data_byte` and `phase`. The stream state advances after each
rising-edge sample, while the pad flops below present the already
computed next value on the following falling edge. Raising `cs_n`
asynchronously returns both variants to byte zero for the next
transaction.

<<SPI streaming: lane logic>>=
generate if (LANES == 4) begin : g_quad
   <<SPI streaming: quad lane>>
end else begin : g_one
   <<SPI streaming: single lane>>
end endgenerate
@

For 4-lane the nibble mux picks the upper nibble when
`phase == 0` and the lower nibble when `phase == 1`, matching
the STM32MP1 QUADSPI indirect-read assembly of
`{first_sample, second_sample}`.

<<SPI streaming: quad lane>>=
reg phase;
initial phase = 1'b0;
always @(posedge cs_n or posedge sclk) begin
   if (cs_n) begin
      data_byte <= 8'd0;
      phase     <= 1'b0;
   end else begin
      phase <= ~phase;
      if (phase) data_byte <= data_byte + 8'd1;
   end
end
assign dout_lane = phase ? data_byte[3:0] : data_byte[7:4];
@

For 1-lane the bit mux picks `data_byte[7 - phase]`, MSB-first,
and mirrors it onto IO0 and IO1. IO2 and IO3 get a constant
`1'b0` data input, so those lanes are held low rather than
floating when output enable is asserted.

<<SPI streaming: single lane>>=
reg [2:0] phase;
initial phase = 3'd0;
always @(posedge cs_n or posedge sclk) begin
   if (cs_n) begin
      data_byte <= 8'd0;
      phase     <= 3'd0;
   end else begin
      phase <= phase + 3'd1;
      if (phase == 3'd7) data_byte <= data_byte + 8'd1;
   end
end
assign dout_lane[0] = data_byte[3'd7 - phase];
assign dout_lane[1] = data_byte[3'd7 - phase];
assign dout_lane[2] = 1'b0;
assign dout_lane[3] = 1'b0;
@

The IO driver uses one explicit iCE40 `SB_IO` per pad. In 1-lane
mode, `NEG_TRIGGER` makes each output flop capture `dout_lane[g]` on
SCLK falling edges, so pad transitions happen half a cycle ahead of
the MP135 rising-edge sample without making the stream counter itself
sensitive to falling edges. In 4-lane mode the pads are unregistered
so the phase mux output reaches the pins directly. Keeping the stream
counter on rising edges matters for long peripheral reads where SCLK
can pause: repeated or idle falling-edge observations re-present the
same computed value instead of advancing the byte stream.

<<SPI streaming: io drivers>>=
genvar g;
generate for (g = 0; g < 4; g = g + 1) begin : g_io
   SB_IO #(
      .PIN_TYPE(LANES == 4 ? 6'b101001 : 6'b100101),
      .NEG_TRIGGER(1'b1)
   ) iob (
      .PACKAGE_PIN(io[g]),
      .OUTPUT_CLK(sclk),
      .OUTPUT_ENABLE(oe),
      .D_OUT_0(dout_lane[g])
   );
end endgenerate
@

=== Pin map

iCEstick pin numbers, mirroring the `qspi` chapter so the same
physical wires reach the MP135 `CN8` connector.

<<spi.pcf>>=
set_io cs_n    56
set_io sclk    45
set_io io[0]   47
set_io io[1]   44
set_io io[2]   60
set_io io[3]   48
@

=== Static pin-drive preflight top

The hardware preflight must not depend on the FPGA UART path. A tiny
one-purpose top lets the MP135 prove the physical QSPI wiring from the
other side: boot the MP135 while the FPGA bitstream is high-impedance,
switch the MP135 QSPI pads to GPIO inputs, then reprogram the FPGA with
static one-hot drive patterns and ask the MP135 to read the six pins.

The bit order intentionally matches the MP135 `g`/`G` commands:
`CLK, NCS, IO0, IO1, IO2, IO3`.

<<spi_pin_drive.v>>=
module spi_pin_hiz (
      inout        cs_n,
      inout        sclk,
      inout  [3:0] io
   );
   wire [5:0] unused;
   SB_IO #(.PIN_TYPE(6'b000001)) i_sclk (.PACKAGE_PIN(sclk), .D_IN_0(unused[0]));
   SB_IO #(.PIN_TYPE(6'b000001)) i_cs_n (.PACKAGE_PIN(cs_n), .D_IN_0(unused[1]));
   genvar g;
   generate for (g=0; g<4; g=g+1) begin : g_io
      SB_IO #(.PIN_TYPE(6'b000001)) iob (.PACKAGE_PIN(io[g]), .D_IN_0(unused[g + 2]));
   end endgenerate
endmodule

module spi_pin_walk #(
      parameter BOOT_TICKS = 48_000_000,
      parameter STEP_TICKS = 24_000_000
   ) (
      input        clk,
      inout        cs_n,
      inout        sclk,
      inout  [3:0] io
   );
   reg [27:0] count = 0;
   always @(posedge clk)
      if (count < BOOT_TICKS + 7 * STEP_TICKS - 1)
         count <= count + 1'b1;

   wire drive = count >= BOOT_TICKS;
   wire [27:0] after_boot = count - BOOT_TICKS;
   wire [2:0] slot =
      (after_boot < 1 * STEP_TICKS) ? 3'd0 :
      (after_boot < 2 * STEP_TICKS) ? 3'd1 :
      (after_boot < 3 * STEP_TICKS) ? 3'd2 :
      (after_boot < 4 * STEP_TICKS) ? 3'd3 :
      (after_boot < 5 * STEP_TICKS) ? 3'd4 :
      (after_boot < 6 * STEP_TICKS) ? 3'd5 : 3'd6;

   reg [5:0] mask;
   always @* begin
      case (slot)
         3'd0: mask = 6'h00;
         3'd1: mask = 6'h01;
         3'd2: mask = 6'h02;
         3'd3: mask = 6'h04;
         3'd4: mask = 6'h08;
         3'd5: mask = 6'h10;
         default: mask = 6'h20;
      endcase
   end

   SB_IO #(.PIN_TYPE(6'b100101)) i_sclk (
      .PACKAGE_PIN(sclk), .OUTPUT_CLK(clk),
      .OUTPUT_ENABLE(drive), .D_OUT_0(mask[0])
   );
   SB_IO #(.PIN_TYPE(6'b100101)) i_cs_n (
      .PACKAGE_PIN(cs_n), .OUTPUT_CLK(clk),
      .OUTPUT_ENABLE(drive), .D_OUT_0(mask[1])
   );
   genvar w;
   generate for (w=0; w<4; w=w+1) begin : w_io
      SB_IO #(.PIN_TYPE(6'b100101)) iob (
         .PACKAGE_PIN(io[w]), .OUTPUT_CLK(clk),
         .OUTPUT_ENABLE(drive), .D_OUT_0(mask[w + 2])
      );
   end endgenerate
endmodule

module spi_pin_drive #(
      parameter [5:0] MASK = 6'h00
   ) (
      output       cs_n,
      output       sclk,
      output [3:0] io
   );
   assign sclk  = MASK[0];
   assign cs_n  = MASK[1];
   assign io[0] = MASK[2];
   assign io[1] = MASK[3];
   assign io[2] = MASK[4];
   assign io[3] = MASK[5];
endmodule
@

<<spi_pin_walk.pcf>>=
set_io clk     21
set_io cs_n    56
set_io sclk    45
set_io io[0]   47
set_io io[1]   44
set_io io[2]   60
set_io io[3]   48
@

=== UART debug top

The `spi_debug` top is a diagnostic wrapper around the normal 1-lane
SPI stream. It does not add any new drive behaviour on the shared SPI
pins: `cs_n` and `sclk` are inputs from the MP135, and the data pins are
driven only by the same `spi #(.LANES(1))` instance used by the regular
bitstream. The only extra output is the iCEstick FTDI UART TX pin.

During a selected frame, the wrapper synchronizes `sclk` and `io[1]`
into the 12 MHz UART clock domain, counts all synchronized rising SCLK
edges, and records the first 32 IO1 samples. When `cs_n` deasserts it
prints:

   SPI E=xxxx S=xxxxxxxx

where `E` is the frame's synchronized rising-edge count and `S` is the
first 32 sampled bits packed MSB-first. This is intended for a slow,
long `p 203` peripheral read so the 12 MHz observer has several
system-clock samples per SCLK period. For a 4096-byte 1-lane raw read,
`E` should be `8000` and `S` should be `00010203` (bytes 0, 1, 2, 3).

The UART transmitter is the existing `uart_tx` module from `uart.nw`;
this wrapper only supplies a small fixed-format byte source.

<<spi_debug.v>>=
module spi_debug #(
      parameter CLKS_PER_BIT = 104
   ) (
      input        clk,
      input        cs_n,
      input        sclk,
      inout  [3:0] io,
      output       tx
   );
   spi #(.LANES(1)) dut (.cs_n(cs_n), .sclk(sclk), .io(io));

   reg        cs_meta, cs_sync;
   reg        selected_prev;
   reg        sclk_meta, sclk_sync, sclk_prev;
   reg        io1_meta, io1_sync;
   reg [15:0] edge_count;
   reg [15:0] last_edges;
   reg [31:0] samples;
   reg [31:0] last_samples;
   reg [5:0]  sample_count;
   reg        frame_done;
   wire       selected = !cs_sync;
   wire       sclk_rise = selected && sclk_sync && !sclk_prev;
   wire       cs_start = selected && !selected_prev;
   wire       cs_stop = !selected && selected_prev;

   initial begin
      cs_meta      = 1'b1;
      cs_sync      = 1'b1;
      selected_prev = 1'b0;
      sclk_meta    = 1'b0;
      sclk_sync    = 1'b0;
      sclk_prev    = 1'b0;
      io1_meta     = 1'b0;
      io1_sync     = 1'b0;
      edge_count   = 16'd0;
      last_edges   = 16'd0;
      samples      = 32'd0;
      last_samples = 32'd0;
      sample_count = 6'd0;
      frame_done   = 1'b0;
   end

   always @(posedge clk) begin
      cs_meta   <= cs_n;
      cs_sync   <= cs_meta;
      sclk_meta <= sclk;
      sclk_sync <= sclk_meta;
      sclk_prev <= sclk_sync;
      io1_meta  <= io[1];
      io1_sync  <= io1_meta;
      selected_prev <= selected;

      if (cs_start) begin
         edge_count   <= 16'd0;
         samples      <= 32'd0;
         sample_count <= 6'd0;
         frame_done   <= 1'b0;
      end else if (sclk_rise) begin
         edge_count <= edge_count + 16'd1;
         if (sample_count < 6'd32) begin
            samples <= {samples[30:0], io1_sync};
            sample_count <= sample_count + 6'd1;
         end
      end else if (cs_stop) begin
         last_edges <= edge_count;
         last_samples <= samples;
         frame_done <= 1'b1;
      end
   end

   <<SPI debug UART reporter>>
endmodule
@

The reporter walks a fixed 23-byte line into `uart_tx` once the observer
has captured the first 32 selected SCLK rises.

<<SPI debug UART reporter>>=
reg pending;
reg report_sent;
reg [4:0] char_idx;
reg tx_start;
reg [7:0] tx_data;
wire tx_busy;

initial begin
   pending    = 1'b0;
   report_sent = 1'b0;
   char_idx   = 5'd0;
   tx_start   = 1'b0;
   tx_data    = 8'h00;
end

always @(posedge clk) begin
   tx_start   <= 1'b0;
   if (cs_start)
      report_sent <= 1'b0;
   if (frame_done && !report_sent && !pending && char_idx == 5'd0)
      pending <= 1'b1;
   if (pending && !tx_busy && !tx_start) begin
      tx_data  <= debug_char(char_idx);
      tx_start <= 1'b1;
      if (char_idx == 5'd22) begin
         pending <= 1'b0;
         report_sent <= 1'b1;
         char_idx <= 5'd0;
      end else begin
         char_idx <= char_idx + 5'd1;
      end
   end
end

uart_tx #(.CLKS_PER_BIT(CLKS_PER_BIT)) u_tx (
   .clk(clk),
   .start(tx_start),
   .data(tx_data),
   .tx(tx),
   .busy(tx_busy)
);

function [7:0] hex_digit;
   input [3:0] n;
   begin
      hex_digit = (n < 4'd10) ? (8'h30 + {4'd0, n})
                              : (8'h57 + {4'd0, n});
   end
endfunction

function [7:0] debug_char;
   input [4:0] idx;
   begin
      case (idx)
         5'd0:  debug_char = "S";
         5'd1:  debug_char = "P";
         5'd2:  debug_char = "I";
         5'd3:  debug_char = " ";
         5'd4:  debug_char = "E";
         5'd5:  debug_char = "=";
         5'd6:  debug_char = hex_digit(last_edges[15:12]);
         5'd7:  debug_char = hex_digit(last_edges[11:8]);
         5'd8:  debug_char = hex_digit(last_edges[7:4]);
         5'd9:  debug_char = hex_digit(last_edges[3:0]);
         5'd10: debug_char = " ";
         5'd11: debug_char = "S";
         5'd12: debug_char = "=";
         5'd13: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[31:28]);
         5'd14: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[27:24]);
         5'd15: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[23:20]);
         5'd16: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[19:16]);
         5'd17: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[15:12]);
         5'd18: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[11:8]);
         5'd19: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[7:4]);
         5'd20: debug_char = hex_digit(last_samples[3:0]);
         5'd21: debug_char = 8'h0d;
         5'd22: debug_char = 8'h0a;
         default: debug_char = 8'h00;
      endcase
   end
endfunction
@

<<spi_debug.pcf>>=
set_io clk     21
set_io tx      8
set_io cs_n    56
set_io sclk    45
set_io io[0]   47
set_io io[1]   44
set_io io[2]   60
set_io io[3]   48
@

=== `SB_IO` simulation model

yosys recognises `SB_IO` as a built-in iCE40 primitive and
needs no help from us during synthesis. verilator does not, so
the testbench is compiled against a stand-alone behavioural
model that covers exactly the configurations our DUT uses
(`PIN_TYPE = 6'b100101` for registered 1-lane pads and
`PIN_TYPE = 6'b101001` for unregistered quad pads, both with
`NEG_TRIGGER = 1`). Any other configuration is rejected at
elaboration so a future change to the DUT does not silently desync
the sim from the synth path.

The model owns one negedge-clocked register per registered pad and
otherwise forwards `D_OUT_0` directly, then gates the selected output
through `OUTPUT_ENABLE`. When the slave releases the bus the inout
port is driven to `1'bz`, and the testbench attaches a `pullup` per
lane to model the master-side MISO pull-up.

<<SB_IO.v>>=
module SB_IO #(
      parameter [5:0] PIN_TYPE    = 6'b000000,
      parameter [0:0] NEG_TRIGGER = 1'b0
   ) (
      inout  PACKAGE_PIN,
      input  OUTPUT_CLK,
      input  OUTPUT_ENABLE,
      input  D_OUT_0
   );
   initial begin
      if ((PIN_TYPE !== 6'b100101 && PIN_TYPE !== 6'b101001) ||
            NEG_TRIGGER !== 1'b1) begin
         $display("ERROR SB_IO sim model only supports PIN_TYPE=100101/101001 NEG_TRIGGER=1, got %b %b",
                  PIN_TYPE, NEG_TRIGGER);
         $finish;
      end
   end
   reg dout_reg;
   initial dout_reg = 1'b0;
   always @(negedge OUTPUT_CLK)
      dout_reg <= D_OUT_0;
   wire dout = (PIN_TYPE == 6'b101001) ? D_OUT_0 : dout_reg;
   assign PACKAGE_PIN = OUTPUT_ENABLE ? dout : 1'bz;
endmodule
@

=== Testbench

Two testbenches, one per `LANES` variant, share the same shape:

  - **CS-high quiet check.** Pulse SCLK twice while CS is high
    and assert that all four `io` lanes read `4'b1111`. The
    pull-ups must win because the slave's `OUTPUT_ENABLE` is
    `~cs_n = 0` and every IOB is tri-stated. This is the
    direct sim of the hardware failure mode --- if the slave
    drives anything when it should not, this check fails.
  - **256-byte frame from cold init.** Every distinct byte
    value 0..255 appears once, master sampling each rise in
    mode 0.
  - **Long frame for byte-counter rollover.** A 4096-byte
    frame wraps `data_byte[7:0]` sixteen times. The real bench
    streams one megabyte per frame, so the sim has to prove
    the counter rolls cleanly at every 256-byte boundary.
  - **CS-high quiet check, again.** Re-asserts that the slave
    releases the bus after the long frame closes.

Each TB is built from named chunks: signals (with master-side
pull-ups), a per-byte sampler that owns the mode-0 sample
point, helpers (`frame` and `cs_high_quiet`), and the scenario
sequencer.

<<tb_spi_1lane.sv>>=
`timescale 1ns/1ps

module tb_spi_1lane;
   <<tb_1lane: signals>>
   <<tb_1lane: byte sampler>>
   <<tb_1lane: helpers>>
   <<tb_1lane: scenarios>>
endmodule
@

The `pullup` instances model the master-side MISO pull-up that
turns "slave does not drive" into a deterministic `4'b1111`
read --- which is exactly what the hardware master sees when
the IOB output enable never asserts.

<<tb_1lane: signals>>=
reg        cs_n = 1'b1;
reg        sclk = 1'b0;
wire [3:0] io;
pullup pu0 (io[0]);
pullup pu1 (io[1]);
pullup pu2 (io[2]);
pullup pu3 (io[3]);
spi #(.LANES(1)) dut (.cs_n(cs_n), .sclk(sclk), .io(io));
integer   errs;
reg [7:0] rx;
@

The byte sampler clocks eight SCLK rises and samples `io[1]`
at each rise (mode 0). The slave drives strongly when CS is
low, overriding the pull-up.

<<tb_1lane: byte sampler>>=
task automatic clock_byte(input integer expected);
   integer i;
   begin
      rx = 8'd0;
      for (i = 0; i < 8; i = i + 1) begin
         #5 sclk = 1'b1;
         rx = {rx[6:0], io[1]};
         #5 sclk = 1'b0;
      end
      if (rx !== expected[7:0]) begin
         $display("FAIL byte %0d: got %02x expected %02x",
                  expected, rx, expected[7:0]);
         errs = errs + 1;
      end
   end
endtask
@

`frame` opens CS-low for `count` bytes; `cs_high_quiet` checks
that with CS high every lane floats to the pull-up.

<<tb_1lane: helpers>>=
task automatic frame(input integer count);
   integer k;
   begin
      #20 cs_n = 1'b0;
      #5;
      for (k = 0; k < count; k = k + 1)
         clock_byte(k);
      #5 cs_n = 1'b1;
      #20;
   end
endtask
task automatic cs_high_quiet;
   begin
      #5 sclk = 1'b1;
      if (io !== 4'b1111) begin
         $display("FAIL cs-high: io=%b expected 1111 (slave should release)",
                  io);
         errs = errs + 1;
      end
      #5 sclk = 1'b0;
   end
endtask
@

<<tb_1lane: scenarios>>=
initial begin
   errs = 0;
   cs_high_quiet();
   cs_high_quiet();
   frame(256);
   frame(4096);
   cs_high_quiet();
   cs_high_quiet();
   if (errs == 0)
      $display("PASS tb_spi_1lane: 4352 bytes plus CS-high checks match");
   else
      $display("FAIL tb_spi_1lane: %0d mismatches", errs);
   $finish;
end
@

The 4-lane TB mirrors the 1-lane shape exactly --- same four
scenarios, same expected byte stream, same pull-up modelling,
same `errs` accumulator --- but the sampler reads all four
`io` lines on each rise and reassembles the byte as
`{first_sample, second_sample}`.

<<tb_spi_quad.sv>>=
`timescale 1ns/1ps

module tb_spi_quad;
   <<tb_quad: signals>>
   <<tb_quad: byte sampler>>
   <<tb_quad: helpers>>
   <<tb_quad: scenarios>>
endmodule
@

<<tb_quad: signals>>=
reg        cs_n = 1'b1;
reg        sclk = 1'b0;
wire [3:0] io;
pullup pu0 (io[0]);
pullup pu1 (io[1]);
pullup pu2 (io[2]);
pullup pu3 (io[3]);
spi #(.LANES(4)) dut (.cs_n(cs_n), .sclk(sclk), .io(io));
integer    errs;
reg [3:0]  first_sample, second_sample;
reg [7:0]  rx;
@

<<tb_quad: byte sampler>>=
task automatic clock_byte(input integer expected);
   begin
      #5 sclk = 1'b1;
      first_sample = io;
      #5 sclk = 1'b0;
      #5 sclk = 1'b1;
      second_sample = io;
      #5 sclk = 1'b0;
      rx = {first_sample, second_sample};
      if (rx !== expected[7:0]) begin
         $display("FAIL byte %0d: got %02x expected %02x",
                  expected, rx, expected[7:0]);
         errs = errs + 1;
      end
   end
endtask
@

<<tb_quad: helpers>>=
task automatic frame(input integer count);
   integer k;
   begin
      #20 cs_n = 1'b0;
      #5;
      for (k = 0; k < count; k = k + 1)
         clock_byte(k);
      #5 cs_n = 1'b1;
      #20;
   end
endtask
task automatic cs_high_quiet;
   begin
      #5 sclk = 1'b1;
      if (io !== 4'b1111) begin
         $display("FAIL cs-high: io=%b expected 1111 (slave should release)",
                  io);
         errs = errs + 1;
      end
      #5 sclk = 1'b0;
   end
endtask
@

<<tb_quad: scenarios>>=
initial begin
   errs = 0;
   cs_high_quiet();
   cs_high_quiet();
   frame(256);
   frame(4096);
   cs_high_quiet();
   cs_high_quiet();
   if (errs == 0)
      $display("PASS tb_spi_quad: 4352 bytes plus CS-high checks match");
   else
      $display("FAIL tb_spi_quad: %0d mismatches", errs);
   $finish;
end
